        <div class="section">
            <h2>About Sikhism</h2>
            <p>Sikhism is a monotheistic religion that originated in the Punjab region of India in the 15th century. It was founded by Guru Nanak and is based on his teachings and those of nine other Sikh Gurus.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="section">
            <h2>Beliefs</h2>
            <p>Sikhs believe in one God, known as Waheguru or Ik Onkar, and reject the caste system. They believe in equality, selfless service, and devotion to God. The ultimate goal is to achieve spiritual liberation and merge with God.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="section">
            <h2>Guru Granth Sahib</h2>
            <p>The Guru Granth Sahib is the central religious scripture of Sikhism. It is a collection of hymns and writings by Sikh Gurus and other saints from different backgrounds. Sikhs consider the Guru Granth Sahib as the eternal Guru.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="section">
            <h2>Five Ks</h2>
            <p>The Five Ks are the five articles of faith that baptized Sikhs are required to wear. They are Kesh (uncut hair), Kara (steel bangle), Kanga (wooden comb), Kachera (cotton undergarment), and Kirpan (a small dagger).</p>
        </div>
